what are your top three expenses? 

Have you ever wondered where the 
avocado toast shame began? It started when millionaire, Tim
Gurner, told millennials if they want to buy a house, they need to stop buying avocado toast.

I hate to break it to you, or anyone who believes that, but that would take a LOT of avocados. 

Something similar is going around with the Latte factor, a nonsensical reason why millennials aren't millionaires. The advice sounds like "skip the latte."

Crunching the math behind these shame filled claims, simply sheds light to what this "advice" really is - shame.

Aside from increasing your income, 
keeping your top three biggest expenses as low as comfortably possible will actually shed years off of your working life. 

Don’t want to cut out anything? That’s cool too if you can afford it forever ❤️

If you want/need to scale back, I suggest starting with the top 3-4 expenses. 

For the Average American, that is housing, transportation, food (and taxes). 

This is how I'm doing it: 
🏡Renting my extra room out and putting that additional income towards my down payment and/or investing. 

🚗downgraded from a gas guzzling car to a used Honda that I negotiated from a private seller that would pay itself off in gas savings alone in 3-5 years. It took me 6 months to find because I had very specific criteria. I also shop around car insurance whenever it goes up, or my mileage usage changes. 

🥫I also set a budget for my groceries, and have lowered my grocery bill from $500/month for just me to $200. 

⚖️Maxing out my 401k to lower my tax liability.

Does a budget sound boring or like a bandage solution to bigger problems? 

I personally think the term ‘budget’ has a PR problem; it gives restrictive, subpar, limiting. 

Having now kept one for the last three years, I can say that our generation needs a reframe — because it’s not inherently restrictive, limiting or makes you live a subpar life. 

Here’s how I think of a budget: a plan for my income. 

That’s it.

Would you ever invest in a company that doesn’t keep a budget? Probably not. 

Why not? — because they have no plan, and they can’t win without a plan 🚩🚩🚩

So then why don’t you have a plan for your income? You also won’t win without a plan. 

There are a few fundamental priorities you should check off, like pay off high debt, build an emergency fund, and save for retirement, but beyond that — you make up the rules! 

Your money plan allows you to get from where you are now to wherever point b is — financial independence? your dream home? car collection? 

You call the shots, but without a plan, you likely won’t get there.

There is a budget method for everyone — whether you have a spending or saving problem, whether you’re meticulous or not, whether you have high debt or are financially independent.

Regardless of what your income is, I can guarantee that a plan will help you in way that is greater than what you might think. 

You may be able to give yourself a raise by simply gaining awareness of your expenses which could result in having the option to retire decades earlier, or you can enjoy higher quality things or experiences now.

I got accused of not being good with money last week because I violated assumption #1. 

Penny pinching and not understanding what enough is is not the vibe here. 

Spending intentionally and making enough are highly individualized, and that’s why I will never specifically call anyone out on what they spend or how much they make. 

BUT as a person who wants you to level up your money life, I WILL always encourage you to set goals, and get on track to reach them. 

Here are some essentials goals that everyone should be on track to reach: 

1. Have enough money to pay for essentials like housing, food, transportation, and bills. 

2. Have discretionary income (money left over after essentials)

3. Be properly protected with insurance (term life if you have dependents, car insurance, renters insurance, health insurance, etc) & an emergency fund.

4. You have a debt pay off plan & are paying them down accordingly.

5. You are contributing towards retirement

6. You have an estate plan 

7. You have other short and long term goals that make you excited about life. 

If you’re on track to meet 1-6, what you spend your money on will be a you and your money thing, and it becomes a trade off with whatever you want to buy vs. #7.

The only time I will give you some tough love is when you spend your money on wants before addressing #1-6 — especially if you have kids, bc you will make their lives unnecessarily difficult.

Be a blessing to your future generation, not a curse. 

I’m on track to retire in my 40’s, have downshifted my career as a result of my financial position, so for someone to say I’m bad with money because I own a designer bag is purely judgmental. 

If you have #1-#6, all I suggest is that your purchases be intentional and make you happy, not guilty. 

We don’t need to judge each other’s discretionary spending. It comes off as sexist, uninformed, condescending, from a place of scarcity, and is just not helpful and will be ignored, so just save your breath and thumb movement instead.

I really have Ramit to thank for hammering this simple concept into my brain. 

My personal finance journey started by me wanting to purchase a home, because I thought that was what people who are good with their money did. 

Boy was I wrong! Do I still want to own a home? Absolutely! Am I still saving for real estate? Yes, but I am now considering an investment property as a priority purchase. 

Buying a primary residence comes with so many phantom costs, it could tie you to a job that limits what your can do with your time, etc. 

I think it makes more sense for me to get a primary residence when 1) the numbers make sense 2) I have a family with elementary school aged kids. 

Always run the numbers; like all of them. 

- Opportunity cost on down payment and sitting reserve for maintenance 
- Maintenance cost (inside and outside) 
- If it’s a bigger floor plan that what you have, you have to furnish, clean, and warm it up
- Taxes, HOA fees if applicable, home owner’s insurance, some towns make residents pay into bonds, interest on mortgage 
- Does it have an impact on your career (because of location)? What are the income and raise ramifications of that? 
- Cost of inflation on maintenance over time 
- Likely appreciation of the home based on the zip code
- Cost of reselling 

You can’t say you’ve ran the numbers by only looking at rent prices vs mortgage cost.

__ what’s a money date? 
Money dates are a great way to stay on top of your finances.  It’s about a 15min-60min date set up to check in on your money behavior (how much you spent, earned, saved, invested), and if you’re on track to reach your financial goals 

Having this reoccurring time for reflection increases your peace of mind and can make you feel like you have a little more control over your finances instead of the other way around. 

__ when do they happen? 
They can happen as little or often as you’d like, but having one at least once a month is the sweet spot in my opinion. 

I personally set a reoccurring calendar invite for every first Monday of the month at 6p. 

— how do you make them not boring? 
I set the mood with a candle, music, and a fun drink. 

__ how do I improve my chances of actually doing it? 
Accountability will help. Do this with a partner or friend that is committed to your success or also needs a sound board/accountability partner. 

What helps me is setting monthly goals that I’m curious to know if I reached or not. This alone brings me to do them. 

__what exactly do you do? 
I have two parts. Part one focuses on closing out last month’s activity and part two is planning for the next month.

👉🏼 Are you making this very common mistake with your raise? 

Most people’s expenses go up at the same rate as their raises.

In other words, they spend ALL of their raise. 

Increasing your expenses as your income increases is called lifestyle inflation

— and it’s important to be aware of it because there’s a few things that need to accounted for like your emergency fund and retirement number. 

You need to update those numbers now that your expenses have changed. 

Very few people are in a position to spend 100% of their raise. 

What’s a better plan that has your current and future self’s best interest in mind?

A good rule of thumb is to put at minimum 50% of your raise towards your financial goals (debt, emergency fund, retirement, etc), and they rest could go towards lifestyle inflation. 

But you’ll need to take your personal goals into account first. 

Some people need a reminder to live their lives
